   \code{"fitted"} \tab Alias for \code{"response"} \tab Alias for \code{"response"} \tab - \cr
   \code{"prob0"} \tab P(y=0 | x) \tab P(y=0 | x) \tab Prob. of failure \cr
   \code{"link"} \tab Linear predictor xb \tab xb / exp(zd) \tab Probit index \cr
   \code{"odds"} \tab Odds = prob / prob0 \tab Odds = prob / prob0. \tab - \cr
   \code{"sigma"} \tab 1 (constant) \tab Std. Deviation: exp(zd) \tab Only available if heteroskedastic \cr
   \code{"variance"} \tab 1 (constant) \tab Variance: exp(2*zd) \tab Only available if heteroskedastic \cr
   \code{"zd"} \tab 0 (constant) \tab Linear predictor zd \tab Linear predictor for scale \cr
}


In binary probit models, the \strong{overall scale} of the latent error term is
not identified and is normalized to 1. In the homoskedastic case there is
no scale equation, so sigma is fixed at 1. In the heteroskedastic case,
the scale equation has no intercept. Therefore, the predicted \code{"sigma"}
and \code{"variance"} represent \strong{individual-level deviations} from the
normalized overall scale, not the absolute standard deviation or variance.

The \code{"link"} type returns the value on the \strong{probit scale}, which is the
inverse of the standard normal cumulative distribution function
(p = Phi^(-1)(p)). This is the linear prediction (p = xb) ih homoskedastic models,
and the standardized linear predictor (p = xb / sigma) in heteroskedastic models.

When \code{se.fit = TRUE}, standard errors are computed using the delta method.
Standard errors are not available (and will return \code{NA}) for \code{"sigma"},
\code{"variance"}, and \code{"zd"} in homoskedastic models.
}
